### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

I would like to be able to detect when a component output has subscribers.

This enables components to dynamically show UI elements like buttons if an output for the button has subscribers.

For example:

```ts
@Component({
    selector: 'app-component',
})
export class ExampleComponent {
    // The button only gets rendered if the output has subscribers
    readonly backClick = output<void>();
}
```

```html
@if (backClick.hasSubscribers()) {
    <button (click)="backClick.emit()">Back</button>
}
```

This is very useful for making components _harder to misuse_, as we don't show buttons that we know have no effect. We can also log warnings or errors if an output should be used, but isn't.

Currently, we can accomplish this by extending the EventEmitter<T> class to refcount on `subscribe()`. However, extending Angular classes is not supported under Angular's semver policy: https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/main/contributing-docs/public-api-surface.md#extending-angular-classes

### Proposed solution

Expose a new property on `OutputEmitterRef<T>`:

```ts
class OutputEmitterRef<T> {
    hasSubscribers: Signal<boolean>;
}
```

The `OutputEmitterRef` would refcount internally with a signal, returning `true` from the `hasSubscribers` signal if the refcount is > 0.

### Alternatives considered

Without this feature, components can use inputs to decide whether to show UI elements.

```html
@if (showBackButton()) {
    <button (click)="backClick.emit()">Back</button>
}
```

This can be used incorrectly.

- If `showBackButton` is set without subscribing, clicking the button does nothing.
- If `backClick` is subscribed without setting the input, the button won't be shown and the listener is dead code.

Alternative: a new argument to the `output<T>()` function.

```ts
output<T>({ refCount: true });
```

This overload would return a new type that has reference counting.

I don't think a new type is strictly necessary as the `OutputEmitterRef` has the ability to reference count subscribers. I am unsure if adding a new property to an Angular class is considered a breaking change.

For example, an application may use `class SomeClass implements OutputEmitterRef<T>`, which would fail to compile if a new property is added.
